							text = "Recently, our country has been diligently conducting research on the historical contribution of the former leader of the DPRK, comrade Kim Il-Sung, as well as the ideas of Juche described by him. The \"Commission for victims and the repressed\", established under your personal protection, has revealed a huge number of human rights violations in the DPRK over several decades of Kim Il-Sung's rule. Now that we are aiming to democratize domestic policy and the course of warming relations with our southern neighbor, we must officially and at the state level get rid of the cult of personality of Kim Il-Sung. However, such a radical turn in relation to the former \"Sun of the nation\" people might not like. Perhaps we should pursue a more gradual policy of \"curtailing the cult of personality\" or delay it altogether?";
							break;
						case 204:
							text2 = "Betrayal of an old friend";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + " the unthinkable has happened! Our loyal ally - socialist China, for which we did not go to full contact with the Soviet Union and did not enter into the CMEA, curtailed the program of assistance to our country. We did not expect such a blow in the back and betrayal, and now our economy will have a very hard time. However, we still have a chance to return the \"old\" China, which has recently survived the protests in Tiananmen, and to persuade it to resume sending humanitarian aid to our country. With the help of our special services, we can eliminate the leader of the Chinese reformers Deng Xiaoping, allowing the conservatives to retain power in China. But the chances of this are small, and, perhaps, with closer relations with South Korea, we will be able to create special economic zones for their entrepreneurs, thereby replenishing the empty budget. And finally, we can rely on our strength and leave everything as it is.";
							break;
						case 205:
							text2 = "Rehabilitation";
							text = "In early 1988, the head Of the Institute of electronic warfare \"Mirim\" O Geun Nel, together with his deputy Kim Yong Chun, was sent to \"retraining\" because of the internal conflict with the current Minister of defense O Jin U. Now that the influence of the generals on the situation in the country is greater than ever, it is worth thinking about strengthening your personal power, then to successfully pass it to your son Kim Jong Il. Perhaps the best idea would be to rehabilitate these soldiers with their support. Moreover, O Kyn Nel was brought up in an orphanage and was under the care of your first wife Kim Jong-Suk and since childhood was a close friend of Kim Jong-Il, so his devotion can not be doubted. But is it worth returning Kim Yong-Chun? While working in the South Korean labor party Committee, he gained a reputation as a firm but loyal reformer. However, their return may be severely affected by the increased influence of O Jin U.";
							break;
						case 206:
							text2 = "The enemy's sanctions";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + " because of our recent nuclear tests, the US and its allies have imposed an embargo on North Korea for the import of fuel, a huge list of luxury goods and military technologies. Our economic situation before the sanctions was very bad, and now I can not even imagine how we can stay afloat. Western leaders demand the complete and unconditional abolition of any nuclear tests and research, as well as the return of experts from the IAEA to the country, and only in this case, trade restrictions will be lifted. However, we can strengthen trade ties with the \"remnants of the socialist camp\", but this is unlikely to help us much.";
							break;
						case 207:
							text2 = "Opening of SEZ";
							text = "The economic situation continues to deteriorate rapidly, so it is necessary to take at least some measures to stay afloat. The few of the reformist wing of our party offers to make concessions to the imperialists and \"slightly open the door\" for foreign investors, allowing them to take advantage of our cheap labor. With such measures, we will be able to fill our empty budget. In addition, we can go a little further and stop being so reckless about small business, artisans and artels, thereby expanding the economic freedoms of our population, but what will the party say? Finally, we can use the most desperate measures, such as sending to planting and construction soldiers on duty.";
							break;
						case 208:
							text2 = "The saving power of the atom";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ", the Soviet Union and the socialist camp have recently been a significant part of world politics, but over the past five years the situation has changed dramatically. The Soviet Union is \"sick\" of separatism in the republics and the protracted economic crisis, and in Eastern Europe workers ' parties can not break the backbone of the growing popularity of the opposition. Perhaps we should hedge and protect ourselves against external world problems, because in the collapse of the world socialist system, we can remain unarmed. I think we need to re-establish our nuclear programme and build a test site, but what will the world community say? In addition, we have other problems in our country; maybe we can allocate this money for more socially useful needs?";
							break;
						case 209:
							text2 = "Difficult hike";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + " despite our attempts to revive the economy through minimal introduction of market mechanisms and joint ventures, the crisis of excessively centralized planned economy and card distribution system has reached its apogee. The country has a severe food shortage, people in the cities are malnourished, and in the province are already starving. We need to take immediate action. It is necessary to import the minimum amount of food necessary for our population, but do we have enough money for this? We can also ask for humanitarian assistance, but we may be asked to suspend nuclear weapons research in return, which will make our situation in the world even more precarious. Or, finally, will we do something in domestic economic policy and introduce a household responsibility system by analogy with China?";
							break;
						case 210:
							text2 = "Japanese Peace";
							text = "Our relations with Japan have always been strained and mostly hostile, ranging from the Korean occupation to Japan's rapidly developing cooperation with the United States and South Korea. Now, when in Japan, not without our help, came to power a coalition of communists and socialists, although very revisionist, it's time to think about the official establishment of relations. Moreover, after the withdrawal of American bases, Japan is no longer involved in any programs to limit trade with socialist countries, so that cooperation with a highly developed country will bring only advantages for our stagnating economy.";
							break;
						case 211:
							text2 = "«Cuba - yes, Castro - no!»";
							text = "Comandante, street riots have been raging in Havana for several weeks against the backdrop of the impending economic crisis. The protesters demand the immediate liberalization of the domestic regime and the opening of borders. And every day the requests of the protesters are becoming more radical. Something must be done. Will we open the borders to all the discontented, as in the days of the \"Mariel crossing\", or will we use force and abandon the people's squads against the protesters? Or do we enter into negotiations with the opposition leaders and satisfy the demands of the Cuban people? Comrade Fidel, we are waiting for your decisive action! If You do not want to resort to such radical measures, then use your popularity and calm the rebellious minds of the masses.";
							break;
						case 212:
							text2 = "Banana republic";
							text = "Comrade Ochoa, the moment has come when we must decide the fate of the Cuban revolution. The planned economy of the Soviet type served us well for the development of social programs, but now even in the most Orthodox socialist countries market elements in the form of cooperatives and artels are being introduced. Perhaps, on the background of general changes, we should also join the trends of change? Moreover, the energy crisis is seriously \"choking\" our economy, and perhaps such small measures will not save it: therefore, the best idea could be a serious decentralization of the economy and the transfer of power to enterprises. In an extreme case, you can introduce a shock therapy. What do you think?";
							break;
						case 213:
							text2 = "Gorbachev's visit";
							text = "A delegation of the Soviet Union headed by General Secretary of the CPSU Mikhail Gorbachev arrived in Havana today, and an official meeting between our countries is about to take place. As you know, we have a very negative attitude to the policy of \"perestroika\" in the USSR and consider it \"apostasy to the West\" and \"restoration of capitalism\". On the background of the deteriorating situation in the socialist camp, we had a chance to criticize Gorbachev and his useless foreign policy again. However, the Soviets will clearly touch on the topic of reducing aid to Cuba, on which we depend very much. Perhaps, if we are not so radical, we will be able to reduce the losses from the Soviet decision. The last word is yours, Comandante!";
							break;
						case 214:
							text2 = "Democracy Soviet-style";
							text = "In the Soviet Union for half a dozen years \"perestroika\" thunders and democratic political transformation is happening. But now the CPSU is rapidly losing credibility, and the democratic coalition and its leader Boris Yeltsin are becoming more and more influential. In addition, thanks to the policy of glasnost, some newspaper publications led by liberals and supporters of Yeltsin, such as \"Moscow news\" and \"New time\", began an active anti-Soviet agitation, actively promoting \"Pro-Yeltsin\" ideas. The problem is that these newspapers are also published in Cuba, and our citizens read these \"harmful publications\". I propose to limit and ban their production in Cuba, so that Cubans read only domestic newspapers and do not think about the superfluous. However, by means of stricter censorship we will reduce our authority of the \"Island of freedom\". We can also counterattack and start publishing anti-perestroika newspapers, but it will have to fork out a little";
							break;
						case 215:
							text2 = "Children of Chernobyl";
							text = "Despite the reduction of aid from the Soviet Union and not the most pragmatic foreign policy of Comrade " + this.global1.sovietPremiereName + ", we are in great debt to the Soviet people, who valiantly helped us get rid of the miserable existence of the Batista era and become one of the most developed countries in Latin America. A few years ago, our Big brother had a disaster – the Chernobyl disaster. It has dealt a serious blow to the health of citizens of the region, especially children. And now the USSR appeals to all governments of the world to provide qualified assistance. It is known that our medicine is one of the leading in the world, and it is time, despite our economic difficulties, to return the favor to the Soviet people and take in seriously ill children to our sanatoriums.";
							break;
						case 216:
							text2 = "Sworn friends";
							text = "For more than thirty years since the victory of the Cuban revolution, the Island of Freedom has been living under many American sanctions and embargoes, and is even on the list of so-called \"state sponsors of terrorism\". But times are changing, the cold war was replaced by a general discharge and thaw in relations between former enemies. Maybe it is time for us to forget all old grievances and resume relations with the United States for the sake of world peace? But is it possible to forget these grievances? The atrocities that were done by the rich Americans to ordinary Cuban citizens? Perhaps it is better to stay out of this \"American world\"?";
							break;
						case 217:
							text2 = "Cuban Democracy Act";
							text = "For three decades, our country has been living under the us embargo, which the US has imposed on false charges. Now the States, under the patronage of Secretary of State James Baker and US Congressman Robert Torricelli because of our alleged aggression once again tighten sanctions against Cuba. \"Cuban Democracy Act\" is the title of an inhuman law of the United States, which was condemned even in the United Nations. It introduced multiple restrictions on trade to Cuba because of imperialists' fictional human rights violations on the \"Island of Freedom\". Our relations with the United States have always been very strained and hostile, but now, in connection with the crisis in the socialist camp, we have become more defenseless. Perhaps we should make concessions to the West, so as not to completely destroy our economy? On the other hand, we have repeatedly come into confrontation with the United States; why should we bend over them this time? Let us condemn their cruelty to the Cuban people! Or... just keep quiet?";
							break;
						case 218:
							text2 = "The End Of Comandante?!";
							text = "Comandante, we're in trouble! After our attempts to pacify the rebellious minds of our citizens, the protests have only intensified, and the demands of the rebels are becoming more radical. There are even calls for your immediate resignation and the immediate democratization of the regime. We must immediately take some action, otherwise nothing good will come out of this. What will happen next?";
							break;
						case 219:
							text2 = "Island of Freedom";
							text = "Cuba from now on is \"Island of Freedom\" again! Thanks to the support of the Cuban people, You, Comrade Ochoa, have succeeded in taking the reins of power into your own hands. But now people are waiting for changes. After all, freedom is a fundamental element of socialism? Moscow demands that we hold free and alternative parliamentary elections, as well as respect for fundamental human rights and freedoms. We will have to start liberalizing sooner or later, but if we \"Unscrew the screws\" too quickly, the people may rush into the arms of the populist opposition. Therefore, maybe restrain the reforms? Or even wait a little longer?";
							break;
						case 220:
							text2 = "Peaceful atom";
							text = "Back in the seventies, Cuba and the Soviet Union signed agreements on \"cooperation in the peaceful use of nuclear energy\", which resulted in the construction of a nuclear power plant in Cuba. It was supposed to be placed in the southern part of the province of Cienfuegos near the town of Juragua. The construction of the NPP really began in the eighties with the support of Soviet, Bulgarian and German specialists. However, plans to complete the construction were thwarted due to the curtailment of the Soviet program of assistance to the countries of the socialist camp. Now that we have a serious regime of energy saving, the power of the atom would benefit. The first reactor is almost ready, and the second half of the work has been done. If we invest in the completion of the project, the consequences of the energy crisis can be much milder for us. However, this event is not cheap: perhaps it would be better to also request the support of experts from the fraternal republics within the project? In addition, we can always just curtail the development of the project.";
							break;
						case 221:
							text2 = "Special period";
							text = "In connection with the reduction of aid from the USSR and the crisis of the socialist camp as a whole, the Cuban economy has seen the beginning of a protracted economic crisis. This is mainly due to the cessation of oil supplies from the USSR at preferential prices and the growth of electricity consumption in recent years. And the instability in fraternal countries seriously affects our economy, which is entirely focused on cooperation within the framework of the CMEA. Now our country is in hard times, and circumstances force us to introduce an analogue of the \"Romanian economy regime\" and reduce oil consumption to the minimum possible. But maybe if we manage to establish closer contacts with the countries of the socialist camp, the impact on our economy will be less painful? What do you think, Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + "?";
							break;
						case 222:
							text2 = "Big brother's betrayal";
							text = "Comandante! Our agents report that there is a brewing conspiracy against you! At the moment, it is known that there are traitors in the government who, with the assistance of the KGB, want to overthrow you and set a course for restructuring according to the Soviet type. Among them are prominent figures of the Communist party of Cuba, such as interior Ministry Colonel Tony de la Guardia and divisional General Arnaldo Ochoa. And it all happened only a month after the visit of Mikhail Sergeyevich! What will happen to our country and party in a year? It is urgent to take any measures against the conspirators! Charge them with corruption and shoot them? Or put them under house arrest to avoid unnecessary dissemination of information?";
							break;
						case 223:
							text2 = "Rome does not pay to traitors";
							text = "Rafael del Pino is a well-known Cuban politician and participant of the Cuban revolution, who under the influence of the perestroika in the USSR began active criticism against the socialist government in Cuba, and then fled to the United States, from where he now continues to broadcast about the dictatorship in Cuba and the cruel actions of the government. And it seems that he is really \"crazy\", as he accuses us of all the troubles of mankind – from drug trafficking to the sale of people into slavery. The worst thing is that Western people believe all this flow of lies. All our \"foreign opposition\" admires del Pino, undermining the prestige of Cuba and the Cuban revolution. Maybe it is time to finally shut him up. We must instruct our agents to eliminate this traitor for the future of Cuba! But what will the West and the USSR say? The murder charges are going to fall on us. As another way out, we can show the world our democracy and disband del Pino to return home. Your opinion, comrade?";
							break;
						case 224:
							text2 = "Paradise island";
							text = "From the Declaration of Independence from Spain in 1898 to the great Cuban revolution, big share of our budget came from the tourism industry - despite the plight of our people, the rampant banditry and the drug trade in Batista's time! Of course, we do not want to go back to the time when our country was a \"brothel for Americans\", but hard times require hard decisions. Perhaps, if we open the doors for Western tourists, we will be able to replenish our empty budget. But don't people pick up from the visitors any bourgeois remnants? Perhaps it would be better to limit the access of our citizens to such events? Or even abandon this idea?";
							break;
						case 225:
							text2 = "Socialism or barbarism?";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + " as you know, the next Congress of the Communist party of Cuba will be held soon. At the previous III Congress, the main goal of the party was to complete the construction of socialism on the basis of Marxist-Leninist ideology. However, times are changing, and on the background of general changes in Eastern Europe, we may need to reconsider our views on socialism and the dictatorship of the proletariat. To remain faithful to the ideals of Leninism or to abandon the secondary positions of Marxism? Or maybe go to Eurocommunism or even, abandoning all the dogmas, take the position of social democracy? The last word is yours.";
							break;
						case 226:
							text2 = "SEZ";
							text = "The economic situation continues to deteriorate rapidly, so it is necessary to take at least some measures to stay afloat. The few of the reformist wing of our party offers to make concessions to the imperialists and \"slightly open the door\" for foreign investors, allowing them to take advantage of our cheap labor. With such measures, we will be able to fill our empty budget. In addition, we can go a little further and stop being so reckless about small business, artisans and artels, thereby expanding the economic freedoms of our population, but what will the party say?";
							break;
						case 227:
							break;
						case 228:
							text2 = "II Congress of the PDPA";
							text = "As you know, the other day, the II Congress of the People’s Democratic Party of Afghanistan should be held. In the eyes of a significant part of the masses, our party has a very bad reputation, some mujahideen leaders call it completely pro-Kremlin, and the presidential regime is imposed from without. If we completely get rid of the dark past of our party and move on to a full-fledged multi-party system, then perhaps we can come to a compromise with a moderate part of the opposition. However, this event is unlikely to please the Khalq wing of our party, which require only moderate Islamic reforms within the framework of socialism. What are we going to do, president?";
							break;
						case 229:
							text2 = "End of war";
							text = "Thanks to the pragmatic work of the government and the enthusiasm of the working people of Afghanistan, the situation in Afghanistan is gradually stabilizing, and peaceful life is returning to cities and villages. The civil war is behind, however, local centers of the opposition continue to partisan in remote mountainous areas, sometimes making sorties and brutally cracking down on civilians. Now that the mujahideen are most vulnerable and deprived of arms supplies from Pakistan, it is time to deliver a decisive blow to the opposition and put an end to this dark period of our history. However, we can, under certain conditions, agree with the mujahideen and offer them freedom, in exchange for their leaders. Or will we use the fragmentation of the opposition and drag more moderate and more loyal people to their leadership? It’s also worth trying to make contact with the unofficial partisan leader Ahmad Shah Massoud, but would he agree? In any case, we can just wait for the mujahideen leaders to fight each other. What do you think about it, president?";
							break;
						case 230:
							text2 = "Negotiations";
							text = "Today, official negotiations between the government of Afghanistan and the moderate part of the opposition, in the person of the Pashtun spiritual leader Sibghatullah Mojaddedi and the chairman of the Islamic Party of Afghanistan Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, should take place. The opposition requires us to hold free parliamentary elections, as well as the organization of a coalition government with «Watan» and other Islamic parties that refuse to cooperate with us. The remaining Khalqists, however, demand that we stop negotiations and shoot down the enemies of the people. What are we going to do, president?";
							break;
						case 231:
							text2 = "«Typhoon»";
							text = "Comrade Najibullah, as you know, in a month, the last division of the Soviet troops will be withdrawn from the territory of our country. The Soviet leadership made the decision to conduct the last large-scale operation, the purpose of which is to inflict maximum damage on the positions of Ahmad Shah Massoud in the north-eastern zone of Afghanistan before the start of the withdrawal of Soviet troops. However, the use of massive aerial bombardments can cause serious damage not only to militants, but also to civilians, which in turn will put us in a not very advantageous position before the mujahideen. Moreover, according to the conclusion of the Geneva agreements, we have an agreement with Ahmad Shah, according to which he will not interfere with the withdrawal of troops, and we will not fight with him. Perhaps we should try to persuade the Soviet leadership not to carry out the operation, what do you think, president?";
							break;
						case 232:
							text2 = "Homeland of terrorism";
							text = "Pakistan agreed to hold regular negotiations with the government of Afghanistan to cut off the supply of weapons to the mujahideen, and today a meeting of delegations should be held in Tashkent, under the guardianship of the USSR and the USA. Our goal in these negotiations, by hook or by crook, is to force the Pakistani side to comply with the Geneva agreements, as well as to force Islamabad to allow Afghan refugees to return to their homeland and not to hinder this. However, the United States, which violates international law by supporting the mujahideen, is unlikely to agree to our conditions, and in any case we will have to make concessions. I hope gracious Allah will help us in a good deed for all Afghan peoples.";
							break;
						case 233:
							text2 = "Land to the peasants, factories to the workers, sanctions to Pakistan!";
							text = "Pakistan, from the very beginning of the civil war in our country, has actively supported (not without the help of the United States) Afghan mujahideen. Spitting on the results of last year’s Geneva Agreements, according to which Afghanistan and Pakistan settled the principles of relations between the countries, especially on the principle of non-interference in each other’s internal affairs, Pakistan continues to send reinforcements to help the opposition. So in June 1988, Pakistani President Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq declared that the Geneva Agreements were «nothing more than a fig leaf». Now that Pakistan has got what it deserves and is fighting fiercely with India, we can enlist the support of our CMEA allies and impose economic sanctions on Pakistan for non-compliance with the agreements, which in turn will cause irreparable damage to the weak Pakistani economy. However, in the socialist camp the midst of change and will they pay attention to us? In any case, we can once again turn to the USSR with a demand to put pressure on Pakistan, but will this bring at least some results? Or continue the «viscous struggle» with the rebels?";
							break;
						case 234:
							text2 = "Exiled king";
							text = "Mohammed Zahir Shah, the former king of Afghanistan, who ruled the country for 40 years and was ousted after the military coup of his cousin Mohammed Daoud, is still popular with the nationalist wing of the mujahideen, despite the fact that he has been in immigration for more than 15 years. Some members of the government propose lifting the ban on the return of the deposed monarch to Afghanistan, which was introduced under Taraki, thereby showing the right opposition the readiness to cooperate. Moreover, if we legalize the National Liberation Front of Afghanistan, the stronghold of all moderate royalists and monarchists, we will deal a serious blow to the ranks of the opposition. However, party members are categorically against such strong concessions and demand to abandon this initiative. The last word is yours.";
							break;
						case 235:
							text2 = "Khalq";
							text = "As you know, during the great Saur Revolution, the main part in the coup was taken by the radical wing of the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan - the Khalq, under the leadership of Taraki and Amin. After the coming of power, the parchamist Babrak Karmal began mass persecution against the leaders and members of the Khalq and now, after the withdrawal of Soviet troops, the confrontation in the party reached a boiling point. According to the Ministry of State Security, some of the Khalq's generals whose secret leader is Defense Minister Shahnawaz Tanai are plotting against you. It is necessary to take measures - to arrest the traitors! But in this case, Tanai can oppose us on behalf of all the khalqists, maybe we need to throw in information about his cooperation with the mujahideen, which our intelligence agencies suggest, thereby getting rid of the unstable wing in the PDPA? Anyway, we can just wait.";
							break;
						case 236:
							text2 = "Tanai's rebellion";
							text = "There is a conspiracy in Afghanistan! Defense Minister Tanai, in agreement with the generals, organized an armed rebellion against you! 20 tanks were deployed to Kabul from Pul-e-Charkhi, and the 8th infantry division was sent from the north-west, and they were about to enter Kabul. What will happen next?";
							break;
						case 237:
							text2 = "The Last Day of Pompeii";
							text = "President, our situation continues to worsen! The opposition breaks through our last frontiers, the soldiers of the people's army surrender and go over to the side of the mujahideen and the attack on Kabul is unfolding in full swing. We need to take some measures, otherwise our Motherland will end! We mobilize the capital, giving the citizens the remnants of weapons, but it is unlikely that untrained workers will be able to oppose anything against professional mujahideen. Or... Again we call the socialist camp, requesting military support? In any case, we can only rely on the will of Allah.";
							break;
						case 238:
							text2 = "The best defense is an attack";
							text = "President " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ", the opposition is on the alert and ready to strike at any moment, maybe we should get ahead of it? If you think that you are ready enough for a counterattack, then we can organize it, but keep in mind that the rebels are too strong and we will have to send reinforcements to help our army for some more time. Where are we advancing, comrade?";
							break;
						case 239:
							text2 = "Many a little makes a mickle";
							text = "After the withdrawal of Soviet troops, our situation continues to worsen, and although the USSR continues to supply us with military and humanitarian assistance, the strength and influence of the opposition continues to grow steadily. Since rebels and counter-revolutionaries are supported by the United States and Pakistan, why not ask for help from our allies? Yes, now crisis phenomena are observed in the Warsaw Pact countries, but if we manage to persuade our partners to supply assistance, then the position of the government army will seriously strengthen. In any case, we can once request assistance from the USSR. What do you think, president?";
							break;
						case 240:
							text2 = "Troop withdrawal";
							text = "According to the 1988 Geneva Agreements, the Soviet Union, for 9 months, was required to completely withdraw a limited contingent of Soviet troops from Afghanistan. And today, the last division of the Soviet army under the leadership of Lieutenant General Gromov must cross the Soviet-Afghan border. For the whole 9 years the USSR has provided us with all sorts of humanitarian and military support, it is necessary to thank the fraternal people for the assistance provided to us, isn't it?";
							break;
						case 241:
							if (this.global1.data[90] != 0 || this.global1.data[92] != 0 || this.global1.data[93] != 0 || this.global1.data[94] != 0)
							{
								int num = -1;
								while (this.global1.data[num + 90] != 1)
								{
									this.global1.data[107] = UnityEngine.Random.Range(1, 5);
									if (this.global1.data[107] > 1)
									{
										num = this.global1.data[107];
									}
									else
									{
										num = 0;
									}
								}
							}
							else if (this.global1.data[81] == 1)
							{
								this.global1.data[107] = 1;
							}
							text2 = "Rebellious mountainous region";
							text = "President " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ", the opposition does not give rest to our people! This time, the opposition invaded the ";
							if (this.global1.data[107] == 1)
							{
								text += "East ";
							}
							else if (this.global1.data[107] == 2)
							{
								text += "West ";
							}
							else if (this.global1.data[107] == 3)
							{
								text += "North ";
							}
							else if (this.global1.data[107] == 4)
							{
								text += "South ";
							}
							text += "region of Afghanistan and begins to sow anarchy there, killing civilians and officials. We must immediately take action and free our motherland from the damned mob. However, we will not destroy the opposition by one strike, and we will have to send reinforcements more than once to help the Afghan army, but in any case, glory to the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan!";
							break;
						case 242:
							text2 = "Eternal revoltuion";
							text = "Comandante! Viva Cuba! Today, exactly 30 years ago, the dictatorial regime of Fulgencio Batista was overthrown during the Cuban Revolution, and popular democracy finally triumphed on our island. In honor of this grand event, millions of Cubans are waiting for your inspirational speech, which will mark the logical conclusion of the celebration of the thirtieth anniversary of the popular uprising. However, the international political situation has changed dramatically: perestroika is underway in the Soviet Union, and the Cold War is coming to an end, as a result of which too radical and careless sayings can cause a flurry of criticism from either the United States or the USSR. In this regard, Gorbachev might not like the assessment of the events of 1959 and the future world revolution, and before his upcoming visit to Cuba, one does not want to spoil relations with the Union. Could it be better to shift the vector of appeal to the people in favor of the need for social change? It will be to the liking of the USSR.";
							break;
						case 243:
							text2 = "Spirit of an era";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + "! It is has been three years, since we, with some success, have started the construction of the 105-story Ryugong Hotel, which was originally planned to be our answer to the construction of the Stamford Hotel in Singapore by a South Korean company, and was supposed to be included in the program of the XIII Festival of Youth and Students. However, due to financial problems, the construction of the hotel was being constantly delayed. Right now, our situation isn't the best, and some Party members are suggesting to halt construction, freezing the project's completion. But this high rise has cost us so many efforts, so, maybe the best idea in this situation would be - to hand over construction to private organizations? What do you think?";
							break;
						case 244:
							text2 = "Agrarian question";
							text = "Due to the fact that over the past 30 years, our agriculture has been seriously interconnected with trade within the CMEA, the destruction of traditional economic contacts has caused significant damage to this industry. In this regard, experts from the State Planning Commission and our economists suggest tackling a radical solution to this issue. Some party members suggest adopting the experience of China, transferring land into the ownership of family contracts, thereby legalizing private trade. Opponents of this idea suggest strengthening the influence of collective farm associations by giving them additional loans for mechanization, but will this help, given the serious energy crisis? The most liberal comrades-in-arms suggest completely discarding all the ideals of Marxism-Leninism, transferring the land to private property or even to foreign investors.";
							break;
						case 245:
							text2 = "The collapse of anti-imperialism?";
							text = "Comrade, as you know, we have been in contact with the Mengistu Haile Mariam regime for a long time, helping the Ethiopian leader repel the attacks of the opposition and Eritrean nationalists. In this regard, our divisions have long been on the territory of Ethiopia, but unlike Angola, in which the internal situation is also unstable, the ruling party of the RPE continues to lose control of the country. Due to the fact that a serious crisis is beginning in our country, some advisers demand from us decisiveness: should we withdraw troops from Ethiopia or support the unpopular regime of Haile Mariam? Some of our military men, who do not believe in the further fate of Ethiopia under the rule of the Workers' Party, offer to support the opposition at all led by the Revolutionary Democratic Party. What do you think, comrade?";
							break;
						case 246:
							text2 = "The party split";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ", after the withdrawal of Soviet troops from the territory of our country, the inter-factional split between radical Khalqists and more moderate Parchamists became more acute in our party. As a result of this, the party’s course is constantly changing due to extremely different views and opinions on the situation in Afghanistan. The preponderance of forces in the party is constantly changing, so some members of the opposing faction are preparing a conspiracy against you. We must act decisively, otherwise it will be too late! We had a great chance to smash and arrest our ideological opponents, but will this not be a catalyst for an even greater catastrophe? Can we manage to solve the problem by more democratic methods?";
							break;
						case 247:
							text2 = "Is there such a party?";
							text = "Despite all our attempts to stabilize the situation in the party and at the front, the situation continues to be extremely deplorable: the opposition does not even think to cooperate, and the bickering continues between the Khalqists and the Parchamists in the party. In this regard, confidence in our party has been undermined, and many adherents of the PDPA are switching to the side of the mujahideen. For a long time, the military, as well as some statesmen, have been demanding the creation of a non-party government, independent of the PDPA, but loyal to the Soviet leadership. Most party members and members of the government advocate the appointment of the influential military Abdul Rashid Dostum to the post of president of the country, while the administration of the party apparatus will remain entirely with " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ". However, is it worth trusting him and what will happen next?";
							break;
						case 248:
							text2 = "Land reform";
							text = "After the April Revolution, the Khalq leadership decided to start a full-scale agrarian reform, the purpose of which was to redistribute the lands of large feudal lords for the free use of peasant families. However, despite good intentions, the reform failed. In the eyes of the conservative population, such a policy was an encroachment of the government on private property, sanctified in their minds by religion and centuries-old traditions, and as a result, armed anti-government opposition gained strength in Afghanistan. The reform was condemned and canceled back in 1986, but no significant changes followed, maybe it is time to return to the agrarian question again? Our party is dominated by several opinions about this: an unshakable continuation of support for the small land peasantry, a review of the results of the reform of 1978, and the beginning of a course to promote cooperation on agricultural land. However, do not forget that a sharp change in the party line can lead to corresponding unrest in society.";
							break;
						case 249:
							text2 = "Course change";
							text = "The situation in the country remains extremely difficult, and the influence of the mujahideen is constantly growing. The opposition refused to negotiate with the government, the desertion trend is spreading at the front, and the decline in Soviet aid has seriously hit our economy. In this regard, the situation forces us to seek help from other countries, but which ones? China, which has not recovered after the events of 1989? Or maybe India, torn by terrorism and social contradictions? We can also improve our relations with the countries of the Arab world, but will it bring us anything? In any case, in such a desperate situation, any provided assistance can help.";
							break;
