							text += " region flared up. In the region, due to growing dissatisfaction with the actions of the government, a large-scale uprising began. Militia and people's squads cannot pacify the armed crowd, which, moreover, begins to rob civilians. Protest leaders are demanding higher wages, resolving the issue of peace and easing censorship, but now we have a hard time, and any easing can seriously affect the situation in the country and only warm up the protests, which, in the end, the opposition can take advantage of. But here is the main question: carrot or stick?";
							break;
						case 251:
							text2 = "Conservative revolution";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ", as you know, things are bad here, but in the socialist camp is even worse. The economic crisis, coupled with a reduction in material assistance from the USSR, caused serious damage to the political situation in the countries of the Eastern Bloc. The countless changes in government, the struggle of the communist parties against the liberal opposition, as well as pressure from Gorbachev, set a precedent for European integration and the fall of the Iron Curtain. But if the Warsaw bloc ceases to exist, then whose help can our country rely on? Who, if not our brothers in socialism, can counter the Western threat? We must mobilize all our forces in order to provide reciprocal support to the allied countries by establishing a Conservative coalition that can conquer the revolution. But at the same time, in the neighboring Soviet Union, there is a fierce struggle between supporters of independence and adherents of preserving the Union, and perhaps it is worth helping conservative politicians in the Supreme Council in their fight with the opposition? Or is it worth it to tackle your internal problems?";
							break;
						case 252:
							text2 = "Prisoners uprising";
							text = "Comrade " + this.global1.politics_name[this.global1.data[11]] + ", I have to tell you bad news. An uprising took place in one of the mujahideen prisoners war camps, and serious amount of weapons were taken by the rebels. After clashes with the garrisons of our army, the rebels were forced to split up, and now they pose a serious threat to nearby villages. Some villages have already received information about attacks on local residents by armed rebel gangs. It goes without saying that we should send militia units in search of rebels, but should we think about the future? The war lasts too long and the number of prisoners of war on both sides is very large, so maybe we’ll start the hostage exchange between the government and the mujahideen? However, some may perceive this as the apostasy and weakness of our army and power, and the number of militants on the opposite side will only increase. Perhaps we will return an uncompromising and trouble-free way to get rid of the problem - «Take no prisoners»? But in this case, we should expect a response. What do you think?";
							break;
						case 253:
							text2 = "Their struggle";
							text = "In Nicaragua, a bloody civil war has been raging for 10 years between the government of the Sandinista National Liberation Front, supported by the Soviet Union, and the opposition government of Contras, sponsored by the United States and its allies. Despite recent government successes in the offensive against the counter-revolutionaries, against the backdrop of perestroika changes in Soviet foreign policy, the Sandinista leadership was forced to negotiate a peaceful settlement. And just a month later, the presidential election will take place, in which, most likely, the SNLF and its leader Daniel Ortega, due to the prolonged economic crisis, will lose to the National Opposition Union led by Violeta Chamorro. We have been helping the government of Nicaragua from the very beginning of the war, and, I think, with the help of our intelligence networks, we could increase their chances of victory. Or will we support the opposition by showing our pro-democratic intentions to the whole world? Alternatively, we can completely ignore the elections.";
							break;
						case 254:
							text2 = "Things are heating up";
							text = "Comrade, unexpectedly for us, in the center of Pyongyang, from all over the city, protesters began to converge, demanding the democratization of the political system, and now more than 200 thousand people gathered in the main square of the country. The rebels easily dealt with the posts of militia who were patrolling the street. Then, breaking through the defenses, they were able to get to The monument to the ideas of Juche, on top of which were hung the flags of South and North Korea, and the latter was missing the red star. We saw such a reception during the protests in Romania, it seems that reactionary and counter-revolutionary forces have reached our country! Our party Propaganda department eats its rice in vain, since they were able to miss the obvious recruitment of our citizens by the forces of the West. In any case, it is necessary to take some decisive measures: disperse the demonstration and destroy any stronghold of the opposition in the form of other parties in our parliament? I think this is a good idea, you do not want to return bourgeois democracy to our «Paradise island», right?";
							break;
						case 255:
							text2 = "The mystery of the socialist atom";
							text = "Former times are a thing of the past, and hopes for the patronage of the USSR is meaningless, given the change of the vector of domestic and foreign policy by Mikhail Gorbachev. Now that our country can remain an orphan in the cruel world of imperialism, we need to look for any means that will help us defend our sovereignty. Of course, I don’t hint at anything, but for 30 years, with varying success, we have been conducting research in the field of nuclear energy, which can play into our hands. However, it is worth noting that despite the successes achieved in this area, we completely lack blueprints for nuclear weapons. Nevertheless, we can mobilize our intelligence networks and contact Socialist Romania on this issue. Or we can bribe officials in a country that is not part of the NPT - India, and thereby get the cherished achievements. In any case, we can limit ourselves to the purchase of new weapons from the socialist camp and thereby establish the production of our models according to the finished model. Or do we also need to join the global trend of «reconciliation» ?";
							break;
						case 256:
							text2 = "The collapse of CMEA";
							text = "Recently, the Council for Mutual Economic Assistance was dissolved, as a result of which the Cuban economy has lost its traditional trade allies and markets for its goods. In the current situation, when the socialist camp is on the verge of destruction, we need to move away from our principles and somehow compensate for this loss. On one hand, we can establish trade with third world countries, but will it help? But on the other hand, our economists argue that the restoration of Cuba's membership in the Organization of American States, from which we were expelled during the introduction of the American embargo, will greatly benefit our economy by integrating it into trade relations between North and South America. However, who is waiting for us there? After all, the OAS is completely controlled by the United States, is it worth it to once again be under their protection? Or will we maintain our sovereignty and reject these proposals?";
							break;
						case 257:
							text2 = "Beloved daughter";
							text = "Comrade Castro, it's time to tackle family employment issues. As you know, your daughter Mariela recently began her (unsurprisingly)rapid career growth in the Communist Party. Her position ... is very different from the usual line of the party, as her views ... are quite exotic for our country. She is a zealous supporter of the Eurocommunist approach to Marxism, third wave feminism, postmodernism and other idealistic nonsense that is gaining popularity in the West, separating the workers and denying the primacy of the class struggle over everything. In addition, Mariela sympathizes with Mikhail Gorbachev and Soviet perestroika, which is very alarming. Father's duty obliges you to help your daughter in her “successful” career by appointing him to some vacant ministerial post. However, will such changes in the party be supported by the government? Perhaps the fate of the revolution is paramount for you?";
							break;
						case 258:
							text2 = "Problems inside";
							text = "Comrade President. Problems are emerging within our Party. As you know, today the Ministry of Internal Affairs is headed by Sayed Gulabzoy, a very tough, independent, decisive, ambitious person, straightforward in actions and judgments, intolerant of other people's opinions if they are at odds with his own. After you came to power, he, already previously intolerant to the moderate faction Parcham, began with all zeal to break the existing balance of power within the Party. And if earlier he simply did not allow the parchamists to occupy any important positions in the MIA, now he is openly preparing a conspiracy against the parchamists, intending to remove them all from their command posts. But balance is a fragile thing, and according to the old agreement, we must divide posts equally between our factions. Maybe it is worth removing Gulabzoy before he does trouble? Instead, it is proposed to appoint either Raza Paktin, the Minister of Water Resources and Energy, who can help us come to an agreement with the tribes, but who is not sufficiently aware of the work of the MIA. Or Assadullah Sarwari, an old acquaintance of Watanjar from the time of serving to Taraki. Sarwari is now in disgrace, but his actions were particularly cruel. And now he will not even mind torturing our enemies in the name of the stability of our power!";
							break;
						case 259:
							text2 = "Kandahar";
							text = "Nur ul-Haq Ulumi has long been the head of the province with the city of Kandahar. Even Soviet specialists noted the effectiveness of his work - the activity of the Mujahideen here was minimal, the situation was stable, and the population received the PDPA warmly. However, his policy also has its drawbacks - Ulumi often did not obey the decisions of the Central Committee, refused to use violent methods, entered into negotiations with the Mujahideen and supplied them with food and finance in exchange for a truce. Moreover, Ulumi is a member of the Parcham faction and, earlier as a military leader, actively advocated the parchamization of the army and the withdrawal of all Khalqists from the armed forces. Now that we, the Khalqists, are in power, Ulumi is showing more and more insubordination and, now, demands to give him autonomy in Kandahar for independent internal political control of the region. But be careful, he has some relatives in the in the Ministry of Defense and General Staff.";
							break;
						default:
							switch (number_event)
							{
							case 363:
								text2 = "Telman will live!";
								text = "On June 19, 1972, the President of the State Council and the Council of Ministers of Cuba, Fidel Castro Ruz, paid a state visit to the GDR and presented the head of the latter, Erich Honecker, with a geographical map on which Cayo Ernest Thaelmann (Ernst Thaelmann Island) and Playa RDA (GDR Beach) were indicated. The renaming of this part of the Cayos Blancos del Sur island chain in the Caribbean Sea was secured by decree No. 3676/72 of the President of the Republic, Oswaldo Dorticos Torrado, and a bust of Telman was also installed on the beach of the island. Now that East Germany has been liquidated and its leaders are threatened with imprisonment (in the same cells in which they once sat under the Nazis), a group of conservative party members are offering to evacuate them to this island and establish a government-in-exile on it in exchange for introducing us some secret SED accounts and access to Stasi agents. The plan provides for the penetration of DI agents into Berlin under the guise of tourists and the abduction of all the functionaries of interest to us with the assistance of Erich Mielke and cosmonaut Sigmund Jähn, but the situation is complicated by the fact that Honecker and his wife are now in the Soviet military hospital in Belitsa (Soviet officers refuse to extradite them and do not let West German prosecutors go there), and his further fate is decided by Mikhail Gorbachev. If we are on good terms with the USSR, then we could ask the Soviet leader to let Honecker go to us for treatment. Or, in order to avoid the interest of the FRG in this object (voices have already begun to be heard that this island is part of the GDR and therefore should be annexed to the FRG), we can simply announce that the transfer of the island was a «formal ceremony» and it still remains within Cuba.";
								break;
