								break;
							case 370:
								text2 = "Disaster «Moby Prince»";
								text = "Urgent news! Today there was another catastrophe off the coast of Italy! Yesterday we heard the news that off the coast of Genoa there was the largest man-made disaster in the history of the country, when the oil tanker MT Haven exploded and, according to various estimates, flooded up to 50,000 tons of crude oil into the sea. Today, the «Moby Prince» ferry crashed near Livorno with another oil tanker «Agip Abruzzo», which has already led to the death of more than 100 people and a possible oil spill of up to 1000 tons. At the moment, the cause of the tragedy is unknown, one of the main versions was the thick fog located in the port. At the same time, some eyewitnesses report some warships and their strange behavior at the time of the collision. How should we respond to this catastrophe?";
								break;
							case 371:
								text2 = "Salus populi suprema lex esto";
								text = "Due to a series of failures that have befallen Italian society over the past few years, the cup of patience of the people dissatisfied with the policies of the CDP was overwhelmed, and people began to take to the streets, led by various left and right organizations. The trigger was published in a number of newspapers compromising information on the current Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti about his active ties with the mafia, as well as involvement in the murder of opposition journalists. A few days later, similar messages began to appear against other members of the Christian Democratic Party. The government has so far kept the situation under control, completely refuting rumors about any connection between CDP activists and criminals, but their situation is extremely difficult.";
								break;
							default:
								switch (number_event)
								{
								case 380:
									text2 = "Mafiusu";
									text = "The problem of organized crime has always been quite acute in Italy. After the end of the Second World War, where many Sicilian bosses openly opposed the Nazis, for many years the government simply turned a blind eye to the mafia problem, and those who did not, could count on help in changing their minds. However, today the situation is beginning to improve. Since 1986, the so-called «Maxi Trial» has been going on in Italy, according to which hundreds of people, one way or another connected with the mafia, have already been convicted, including several high-ranking bosses, for more than 2000 years. However, despite some progress in this case, immediately after the heavy sentences were passed, a wave of appeals began, thanks to which many honest and not very citizens managed to protest the decision against them. For our part, we could help the Italian authorities in resolving this age-old problem, with various consultations and agent connections through the law enforcement agencies of our countries. At the same time, some of our intelligence officers, on the contrary, believe that the pacification of internal political life in Italy, which will occur as a result of these processes, can undermine the growing mood in Italian society and therefore we could help eliminate the most zealous judges participating in this process and demanding maximum punishment. for criminals.";
									break;
								case 381:
									text2 = "Libertas";
									text = " After the Risorgimento, San Marino has always had close ties with Italy, with which it has a continuous border and is located, as it were, inside its territory. That is why, when the ideas of socialism began to capture the minds of Italian citizens, similar processes began to take place in the proud independent republic. Due to the strong communist resistance during the Second World War, the local Communist Party managed to gain a fairly firm foothold in local political life and even for a long time to be in ruling coalitions with the Socialists. The popularity of the party was so high that it did not decrease even after the actual Italian invasion in 1957, when the local Christian party, under pressure from Rome, took power into its own hands. At the same time, being heavily dependent on the Italian Communist Party, the Eurocommunist wing became increasingly influential, as a result of which in the 70s and 80s it created a ruling coalition with the Christian Democrats. Now, after a rather serious success in the elections the year before last, where the Communist Party managed to gain 29% of the vote, it again entered into a coalition with the HDP. Against the background of an increasing departure from socialism in the countries of the Eastern camp and the perestroika processes in the Italian Communist Party, many San Marino party members are seriously considering a complete transition to social democratic positions, with a departure from Marxism and communism in general, in order to get even more votes. At the same time, the positions of the \"Orthodox\" continue to remain strong in the party, and, if necessary, we could use them to prevent the final turn of the party to the right. But do we need to interfere in the affairs of such a tiny state?";
									break;
								case 382:
									text2 = "Vita sine libertate, nihil!";
									text = " The ongoing protests in Italy are getting hotter and leading to more victims. On the outskirts of the country, the police almost completely lost control over the situation, not having time to catch looters and bandits who raised their heads. One of their victims was an elderly Japanese couple beaten to death by robbers after refusing to hand over an old watch. In the center of the country, the situation is not much better - in many cities, their own tent cities have appeared, trying to create a parallel government that strongly opposes the lawlessness of Andreotti and his cabinet. Paradoxically, local communal and local government services continue to perform their duties, having actually abandoned the ongoing clashes.";
