						case 1078:
							text2 = "Workers Lepenism";
							text = "The surge of leftist sentiments throughout Europe again, as in the already distant 1968, swept across France, where student demonstrations against the current government took place. Socialist President François Mitterrand, according to protesters, is pursuing a \"neo-imperialist policy\" towards the former African colonies and, contrary to election promises, is moving towards neoliberal reforms, curtailing the rights of trade unions and workers. After lengthy attempts to disperse student rallies, Mitterrand, not wanting a repeat of the bloody events of 1968, decided to dissolve parliament and hold new elections. But according to the results of the vote, \"Front de gauche\" won only 6% of the vote, while the bloc of communists and socialists of Mitterrand took 33%. However, unexpectedly for everyone, the leader of the vote was the \"National Front\", a poujadist party created by Jean-Marie Le Pen. Together with the gaullist parties, the right-wing coalition managed to gain 55% of the vote. Having got a crushing defeat in the elections, the leftist coalition actually collapsed, and, because of the rumor about President Mitterrand's illness, which he had been hiding for 15 years, the question of the country's leader's further legal capacity became the main agenda. Mitterrand had to resign and announce a new presidential election, where Jean-Marie Le Pen successfully won the second round, beating his main rival, the socialist Lionel Jospin, by a few percent. At the same time, in the former French colony, Algeria, the Democrats won the parliamentary elections, overtaking the Islamists and socialists from the FLN. Some see the \"hand of Paris\" here, as liberals in Algeria tend to cooperate with the former metropolis.";
							break;
						case 1079:
							text2 = "First elections";
							text = "The first parliamentary elections after German reunification are due to take place this month. The Bundestag added almost 150 seats to represent the annexed eastern states of Germany without reducing the number of western members. For the former GDR and West Berlin, a 5% threshold separate from the federal one was applied. Analysts predict a landslide victory for the Christian Democrats, whose leader, Helmut Kohl, is now associated with the \"unifier of the German people.\" However, a pan-European rise in leftist sentiment also guarantees a significant majority of votes for the Social Democrats, PDS and the \"Union of the 90s/Greens coalition\". The electoral intrigue still persists, but it is still difficult to say whether West German politics is ready to come to terms with the East one.";
							break;
						case 1080:
							text2 = "New Entente";
							text = "These are difficult times. The position of the socialist bloc is deteriorating, and in addition to this, our allies in the bloc reacted ambiguously to the return of the monarch to our country. However, we are not alone in this situation. Bulgaria was also condemned for the return of the monarch, and Hungary in general is shaken by unrest because of the lost war. This can serve as a pretext for the creation of an unspoken alliance of mutual assistance between our countries. However, is it worth it, because it is not clear how our allies in the bloc will react to this?..";
